snippet.textDisplay: My partner for the last 3 years asked me for a break cause he was confused about our relationship; this was 3 weeks ago. After talking everything out (a week of hours of intimate conversations) I decided to give him the break and move out of the apt we were renting together and moved back with my family. He said he loved me so much but he has some personal issues he needs to resolve before continuing with me. He said he wants to fight for me and show me how much he loves me after he looks for help with a professional psychologist. Thus, he left me with hope that his love is true and he truly just is confused. 5 days after the separation (1st week of quarantine), over a phone call, he confessed he cheated on me and my heart burst into a million pieces. Now I truly understand why he wanted the break. He said he regrets everything and that is why he wants to find help, cause he knows he has unresolved issues within himself that lead to his infidelity and not giving me his all. Now I am in the 2nd week of quarantine and dealing with all of this;  locked in doors really puts things in perspective. If he truly loved me, he would want to solve and push through this together. But I also respect the fact that he admits he has issues. Idk if I should believe he will prove to me and fight for me that he loves me. And that is the hardest part. I never saw this coming. All I know that I need to value myself and push forward for myself. I gave him my all and in the process I lost a chunk of myself. Now I’m recovering my self love and relearning about myself... see how I can achieve my goals. If he does fight for me, then I’ll deal with it later... but for now... it is me, myself, and I.

snippet.textDisplay:
Life is a Theater. Invite your audience carefully.

Not everyone is spiritual or emotionally healthy enough to have a front row seat in our lives.

There are some people in your life that are best loved from a distance.
...
It's amazing what you can accomplish when you let go, or at least minimize your time with draining, negative, incompatible, pointless relationships, friendships and fellowships!

Consider your current relationships:
Pay attention to who lifts and who leans...
Who encourages and who discourages...
Who is on a path of growth and who is going down fast...

When you leave certain people, do you feel better or feel worse?

Who always has drama?

With love and truth around you, the easier it will become for you to decide who gets to sit in the FRONT ROW and who should be moved to the balcony of your Life.

You cannot change the people around you, but you can change the people you are around!

Let Your Haters Be Your Motivators (but let them do it from afar).

Life is a Theater invite your audience carefully.

It's okay to be vulnerable. That's how we grow as people and you are right, Liane. Everything does happen for a reason. I know you'll heal from this and forgiving is the only way to do it. I like to metaphorically compare forgiving someone to a scar. After its healed, you can see the scar but it doesn't hurt when you touch it. It doesn't matter how much time and effort you've invested in a relationship. You can give this person the world and the universe, but if that person isnt meant to be yours, he/she won't be and that's a scary thought. In the end, when you know you've given it your all, you walk out of this relationship knowing you did your best and have no regrets.
